seType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Full blood examination (FBE)","Blood group antibody screen","75g glucose tolerance test","Group B Streptococcus swab","Blood pressure measurement"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAt 28 weeks gestation, several routine investigations are performed including \u003Cstrong\u003Efull blood examination\u003C/strong\u003E to check for anaemia, \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood group antibody screen\u003C/strong\u003E to detect antibodies that may cause haemolytic disease of the newborn, and \u003Cstrong\u003E75g glucose tolerance test\u003C/strong\u003E to screen for gestational diabetes. \u003Cstrong\u003EGroup B Streptococcus (GBS) screening\u003C/strong\u003E is performed later in pregnancy at 35-37 weeks gestation, as colonisation status can change over time. \u003Cstrong\u003EBlood pressure measurement\u003C/strong\u003E is performed at every antenatal visit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGBS screening is done closer to term because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EColonisation status can be transient\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EResults are most predictive of GBS status at delivery when collected within 5 weeks of birth\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThis timing allows for appropriate antibiotic prophylaxis planning during labour if needed\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Group B Streptococcus screening is performed at 35-37 weeks gestation, not at 28 weeks","28-week antenatal screening includes full blood examination, antibody screen, and glucose tolerance test"],"references":["Pangerl S, Sundin D, Geraghty S. Adherence to screening and management guidelines of maternal Group B Streptococcus colonization in pregnancy. J Adv Nurs. 2022 Oct;78(10):3247-3260. doi: 10.1111/jan.15249. Epub 2022 Apr 15. PMID: 35429021; PMCID: PMC9546437.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics an